ce:section.ce:para:
Bio-based polymers can not only replace existing petroleum-based polymers in function, but show superior performance compared with existing polymers, which has attracted extensive attention [34-41]. Cellulose is the most abundant renewable and biodegradable material in nature among readily available renewable bio-based materials [42]. Usually, it can be observed blue luminescence under UVirradiation, which due to the hydrogen bonds in the molecular structure formed by large number of hydroxyl units that both rigidify molecular conformations and promote the short contact of nonconventional chromophores. [43]. In addition, Yuan group reported the crystal of cellulose model compound exhibits remarkable pRTP under ambient conditions on account of they formed various oxygen clusters with rigid conformation [44]. Accordingly, cellulose derivatives have the potential of preparing pRTP materials. Carboxymethyl cellulose (CMC) is modified cellulose by carboxymethylation, which has better solubility, film formation and more abundant active sites [45-48], so it is the ideal choice for graft reaction with various luminescent groups as substrate. Here, we developed a series of cellulose-based amide grafting reaction system (Fig. 1
                     a). The rigid microenvironment provided by the semi-rigid cellulose chains and intermolecular interactions, which stabilized triplet excitons and minimized nonradiative transitions, maintaining long lifetimes even in the amorphous state (Fig. 1b-c). Using benzene or different polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons as grafted groups enables tuning of afterglow color from blue-green to red, and the performance of dynamic pRTP can be adjusted by space stacking effect (Fig. 2
                     ). In addition, the films obtained by hot pressing drying method has excellent mechanical properties. Consequently, cellulose-based films have the characteristics of large-scale preparation, biodegradation and photo-responsiveness, which could be applied to large-scale display and multiple information encryption.
